i have created my conatct part of my portfolio niw i want to add backend for handling contact
ChatGPT said:

Perfect! To handle the contact form on your portfolio, you need a backend that can receive the submitted data (like name, email, message) and do something with it, usually one of these:

  1. Send an email to you

  2. Store it in a database

  3. Both

Ill guide you step by step for a simple Node.js + Express backend that emails you the contact form data (you can later expand it to store in a database if needed).

1 Set up Node.js project

In your project folder:

bash
mkdir backend
cd backend
npm init -y
npm install express nodemailer cors body-parser dotenv

  • express backend framework

  • nodemailer to send emails

  • cors allow frontend to call backend

  • body-parser parse JSON form data

  • dotenv store sensitive data (like email/password)

2 Create .env file

In the backend folder:

ini
EMAIL_USER=your_email@gmail.com
EMAIL_PASS=your_email_password_or_app_password

Tip: If using Gmail, create an App Password for security. Dont use your main Gmail password.

3 Create server.js

js
const express = require("express");
const nodemailer = require("nodemailer");
const cors = require("cors");
require("dotenv").config();

const app = express();
const PORT = 5000;

app.use(cors());
app.use(express.json());

// Contact route
app.post("/contact", async (req, res) => {
  const { name, email, message } = req.body;

  if (!name || !email || !message) {
    return res.status(400).json({ msg: "Please fill all fields" });
  }

  try {
    const transporter = nodemailer.createTransport({
      service: "gmail",
      auth: {
        user: process.env.EMAIL_USER,
        pass: process.env.EMAIL_PASS,
      },
    });

    const mailOptions = {
      from: email,
      to: process.env.EMAIL_USER,
      subject: `Contact Form Message from ${name}`,
      text: message,
    };

    await transporter.sendMail(mailOptions);
    res.status(200).json({ msg: "Message sent successfully!" });
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    res.status(500).json({ msg: "Server error, please try again later." });
  }
});

app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));

4 Connect your frontend

In your contact form submit handler (React example):

js
const handleSubmit = async (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  
  const data = { name, email, message };

  try {
    const res = await fetch("http://localhost:5000/contact", {
      method: "POST",
      headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
      body: JSON.stringify(data),
    });

    const result = await res.json();
    alert(result.msg);
  } catch (err) {
    alert("Error sending message!");
  }
};

Now your contact form will send emails to your inbox!

If you want, I can also show you how to save the messages in a database like MongoDB so you have a record of all submissions.

Creating a .env file is simple! Its just a plain text file where you store sensitive information (like email passwords) that you dont want to put directly in your code. Heres how to do it:

1 Inside your backend folder

Go to your backend folder:

bash
portfolio/backend/

2 Create a new file named .env

  • On Windows:

    1. Right-click New Text Document

    2. Name it .env (make sure its not .env.txt)

  • On Mac/Linux:

    bash
    touch .env

3 Add your environment variables

Open .env in a text editor and add:

ini
EMAIL_USER=your_email@gmail.com
EMAIL_PASS=your_email_password_or_app_password

  • EMAIL_USER your email address where you want to receive messages

  • EMAIL_PASS your email password or app password (Gmail requires App Passwords if 2FA is enabled)

Example:

ini
EMAIL_USER=myportfolio@gmail.com
EMAIL_PASS=abcd1234app

4 Make sure .env is ignored by Git

Add this line to your backend/.gitignore:

bash
.env

This ensures your passwords arent uploaded to GitHub.

Once .env is ready, your server.js can use it like this:

js
require("dotenv").config();

console.log(process.env.EMAIL_USER); // should print your email

Perfect! Using EmailJS is a great way to handle your contact form without needing an email password or backend server. You can send emails directly from your React frontend. Ill guide you step by step.

1 Sign up and set up EmailJS

  1. Go to https://www.emailjs.com/ and create a free account.

  2. After logging in:

    • Go to Email Services Add Email Service connect your email (Gmail, Outlook, etc.)

    • Go to Email Templates Create Template design your email layout (use placeholders for name, email, message)

2 Get your credentials

Youll need 3 things:

  1. Service ID from Email Services (e.g., service_abc123)

  2. Template ID from your email template (e.g., template_xyz456)

  3. Public Key from EmailJS dashboard (e.g., user_123abc)

3 Install EmailJS in your React project

bash
npm install @emailjs/browser

4 Update your React contact form

Example ContactForm.js:

jsx
import React, { useRef } from "react";
import emailjs from "@emailjs/browser";

const ContactForm = () => {
  const form = useRef();

  const sendEmail = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    emailjs.sendForm(
      "YOUR_SERVICE_ID",
      "YOUR_TEMPLATE_ID",
      form.current,
      "YOUR_PUBLIC_KEY"
    )
    .then(
      (result) => {
        console.log(result.text);
        alert("Message sent successfully!");
      },
      (error) => {
        console.log(error.text);
        alert("Failed to send message, try again.");
      }
    );
  };

  return (
    <form ref={form} onSubmit={sendEmail}>
      <input type="text" name="user_name" placeholder="Your Name" required />
      <input type="email" name="user_email" placeholder="Your Email" required />
      <textarea name="message" placeholder="Your Message" required />
      <button type="submit">Send</button>
    </form>
  );
};

export default ContactForm;

5 Update your template placeholders

  • Make sure your template in EmailJS uses user_name, user_email, and message (same as in your form name attributes).

ChatGPT said:

Perfect! I see your current Contact component is fully frontend-only and already has a fun mascot animation. Since you want to connect it to EmailJS (so you dont need a backend), Ill rewrite your component so it sends messages directly from React.

Heres the ready-to-use EmailJS version:

jsx
import React, { useState, useRef } from "react";
import "../App.css";
import emailjs from "@emailjs/browser";

const Contact = () => {
  const [coverEyes, setCoverEyes] = useState(false);
  const [submitted, setSubmitted] = useState(false);
  const form = useRef();

  const handleMessageChange = (e) => {
    if (e.target.value.length > 0) {
      setCoverEyes(true);
    } else {
      setCoverEyes(false);
    }
  };

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    emailjs
      .sendForm(
        "YOUR_SERVICE_ID",   // replace with your EmailJS service ID
        "YOUR_TEMPLATE_ID",  // replace with your EmailJS template ID
        form.current,
        "YOUR_PUBLIC_KEY"    // replace with your EmailJS public key
      )
      .then(
        (result) => {
          console.log(result.text);
          setSubmitted(true);
        },
        (error) => {
          console.log(error.text);
          alert("Failed to send message, please try again.");
        }
      );
  };

  return (
    <section className="contact-section">
      <h2 className="contact-title">Contact Me</h2>

      {/* Mascot */}
      <div className="animal-container">
        {!submitted ? (
          <div className={`animal ${coverEyes ? "cover-eyes" : ""}`}></div>
        ) : (
          <div className="animal thankyou"> Thank you! Bhanu will reply soon </div>
        )}
      </div>

      {/* Contact Form */}
      <form ref={form} className="contact-form" onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
        <input type="text" name="user_name" placeholder="Your Name" required />
        <input type="email" name="user_email" placeholder="Your Email" required />
        <input type="text" name="contact_number" placeholder="Contact Number" required />
        <textarea
          name="message"
          placeholder="Write your message..."
          rows="4"
          onChange={handleMessageChange}
          required
        />
        <button type="submit">Send Message</button>
      </form>
    </section>
  );
};

export default Contact;

ChatGPT said:

Perfect! Lets enhance your contact form to make it more interactive and user-friendly. Well do three things:

  1. Clear the form after submission

  2. Show a nice popup/animation instead of alert()

  3. Add a loading state while the email is being sent

Heres the updated Contact.jsx code:

jsx
import React, { useState, useRef } from "react";
import "../App.css";
import emailjs from "@emailjs/browser";

const Contact = () => {
  const [coverEyes, setCoverEyes] = useState(false);
  const [submitted, setSubmitted] = useState(false);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false); // Loading state
  const form = useRef();

  const handleMessageChange = (e) => {
    setCoverEyes(e.target.value.length > 0);
  };

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    setLoading(true); // start loading

    emailjs
      .sendForm(
        "YOUR_SERVICE_ID",
        "YOUR_TEMPLATE_ID",
        form.current,
        "YOUR_PUBLIC_KEY"
      )
      .then(
        (result) => {
          console.log(result.text);
          setSubmitted(true);
          setLoading(false); // stop loading
          form.current.reset(); // clear the form
        },
        (error) => {
          console.log(error.text);
          setLoading(false); // stop loading
          alert("Failed to send message, please try again.");
        }
      );
  };

  return (
    <section className="contact-section">
      <h2 className="contact-title">Contact Me</h2>

      {/* Mascot */}
      <div className="animal-container">
        {!submitted ? (
          <div className={`animal ${coverEyes ? "cover-eyes" : ""}`}></div>
        ) : (
          <div className="animal thankyou">
             Thank you! Bhanu will reply soon 
          </div>
        )}
      </div>

      {/* Contact Form */}
      <form ref={form} className="contact-form" onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
        <input type="text" name="user_name" placeholder="Your Name" required />
        <input type="email" name="user_email" placeholder="Your Email" required />
        <input type="text" name="contact_number" placeholder="Contact Number" required />
        <textarea
          name="message"
          placeholder="Write your message..."
          rows="4"
          onChange={handleMessageChange}
          required
        />
        <button type="submit" disabled={loading}>
          {loading ? "Sending..." : "Send Message"}
        </button>
      </form>

      {/* Optional popup animation */}
      {submitted && (
        <div className="popup">
          <p> Message sent successfully! Bhanu will reply soon </p>
        </div>
      )}
    </section>
  );
};

export default Contact;

Whats new

  1. Loading state:

js
const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  • Button text changes to Sending... while the email is being sent.

  • Button is disabled during sending to prevent multiple clicks.

  1. Clear form:

js
form.current.reset();

  1. Popup instead of alert:

  • A small <div className="popup"> shows the success message.

  • You can style it in App.css for animations or fade-out effect.

Optional CSS for popup

Add this to App.css:

css
.popup {
  position: fixed;
  top: 20px;
  right: 20px;
  background: #4caf50;
  color: white;
  padding: 15px 20px;
  border-radius: 10px;
  animation: fadeInOut 3s forwards;
  z-index: 1000;
}

ChatGPT said:

Ah! That message comes from the error callback in EmailJS, which means your form did not successfully send the email. Lets troubleshoot step by step:

1 Check your EmailJS credentials

Make sure you replaced these exactly in your Contact.jsx:

js
emailjs.sendForm(
  "YOUR_SERVICE_ID",   // from EmailJS dashboard  Email Services
  "YOUR_TEMPLATE_ID",  // from EmailJS dashboard  Email Templates
  form.current,
  "YOUR_PUBLIC_KEY"    // from EmailJS dashboard  Integration  API Keys
)

Common mistakes:

  • Typos in the IDs

  • Using the Service Name instead of Service ID

  • Using the wrong Template ID

2 Match template variable names

In your EmailJS template, you must have placeholders exactly matching your form input name attributes:

html
<input type="text" name="user_name" />
<input type="email" name="user_email" />
<input type="text" name="contact_number" />
<textarea name="message"></textarea>

And in the EmailJS template:

css
Name: {{user_name}}
Email: {{user_email}}
Contact: {{contact_number}}
Message: {{message}}

Even a small typo (like username vs user_name) will break it.

3 Test in EmailJS Email Template Test

  1. Go to your template in EmailJS Test Template

  2. Fill in dummy data and click Send Test

  3. If it fails the issue is with service connection (your email service setup).

4 Browser CORS / Vite issues

EmailJS is frontend-only, so make sure:

  • You are running your React app with npm start

  • No network blockers or browser extensions are blocking requests

5 Check console for error

In your browser, open DevTools Console and see what error.text says:

js
(error) => {
  console.log(error.text);  // this gives detailed error from EmailJS
}

It will usually tell you if its:

  • Invalid Service ID

  • Invalid Template ID

  • Invalid Public Key

import React from "react";
import "../App.css";

const ExperienceCard = ({ role, company, duration, details, certificateLink }) => {
  return (
    <div className="flip-card">
      <div className="flip-card-inner">
        {/* Front */}
        <div className="flip-card-front">
          <h3>{role}</h3>
          <h4>{company}</h4>
          <p className="duration">{duration}</p>
        </div>

        {/* Back */}

          {certificateLink && (
            <a href={certificateLink} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              View Certificate
            </a>
          )}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};
